  "prompt": "What is nerve cell?",
  "response": "A nerve cell, also known as a neuron, is the fundamental unit of the nervous system. Neurons are specialized cells that transmit electrical and chemical signals throughout the body, enabling communication within the nervous system. Each neuron typically consists of three main parts:\n\n1. **Cell Body (Soma)**: Contains the nucleus and other organelles, and is responsible for maintaining the cell's health and functionality.\n\n2. **Dendrites**: Branch-like structures that receive messages from other neurons and transmit these signals to the cell body.\n\n3. **Axon**: A long, thread-like projection that transmits electrical impulses away from the cell body to other neurons, muscles, or glands. The axon can be covered by a myelin sheath, which acts as an insulator to speed up the transmission of nerve impulses.\n\nNeurons communicate through synapses, which are junctions where the axon terminal of one neuron meets the dendrite or cell body of another. Chemical neurotransmitters are released from the axon terminals into the synapse, binding to receptor sites on the receiving neuron, thereby continuing the transmission of the signal.\n\nThe collective activity of neurons underpins all aspects of nervous system function, including sensory perception, motor control, cognition, and autonomic regulation of bodily functions.",
